{
  "q1_accurate": [
    {"tool": "sense_search", "query": "immutable metadata attributes attached during name resolution", "note": "Located attributes.Attributes at attributes/attributes.go:41 and Attributes.Equal at :90 on the first query — the exact type and comparison site the whole ticket was about, from a conceptual phrasing that named neither."},
    {"tool": "sense_graph", "query": "attributes.Attributes (direction=callers)", "note": "composed_by gave me the three carrier types with exact refs — resolver.Address:91, resolver.Endpoint:186, resolver.State:196 — plus a depth-2 layer that pre-seeded most of the Task 4 holder list (grpc.addrConn clientconn.go:1242, pickfirst.scData:153, addressList:876, resolver.AddressMapV2 map.go:43, endpointData:185, endpointsharding.ChildState:44, outlierdetection.subConnWrapper:33, transport.http2Client:71, cdsbalancer:122)."},
    {"tool": "sense_graph", "query": "xds.SetXDSHandshakeClusterName (direction=callers)", "note": "Pinned the Task 3 attach point precisely: clusterimpl.clusterImplBalancer.NewSubConn at clusterimpl.go:571 with the call site snippet at :575, and correctly separated the two test callers from the one production caller."},
    {"tool": "sense_graph", "query": "grpc.addrConn (direction=both)", "note": "Surfaced copyAddresses (clientconn.go:894) and equalAddressesIgnoringBalAttributes (clientconn.go:1012) as callees with their call-site lines — the shallow-copy aliasing fact and the keep-vs-teardown guard at :1027 became the two highest-risk items in Task 6, and I would not have thought to look for either."},
    {"tool": "sense_graph", "query": "resolver.State / resolver.Endpoint (direction=callers)", "note": "composed_by depth-2 gave the replay-holder set I ranked as Tier 4: balancergroup.subBalancerWrapper:44, lazy.lazyBalancer:71, priority.childBalancer:33, rls.rlsBalancer:161, manual.Resolver:44, ccResolverWrapper:36, delegatingResolver:52, xdsresource.DNSUpdate:95."},
    {"tool": "sense_blast", "query": "attributes.Attributes", "note": "The retained_via_interfaces block is the one thing that made Task 5 possible — it named clusterimpl.scWrapper (clusterimpl.go:563) via SubConn, endpointsharding.balancerWrapper via ClientConn, balancergroup.Options via ClientConn, grpclb.subConnCacheEntry (grpclb_util.go:47) via SubConn, weightedroundrobin.endpointWeight (balancer.go:516) via SubConn. Its direct_callers list also enumerated the attribute setters I used to build the Task 6 §3 value inventory (state.Set state.go:41, proxyattributes.Set:41, networktype.Set:33, ringhash.HashKey attr.go:57, xdsclient.SetClient attributes.go:33)."}
  ],
  "q1_wrong": [
    {"tool": "sense_blast", "query": "attributes.Attributes", "note": "direct_callers is heavily polluted with false positives — aes128gcm.Encrypt, advancedtls.scanCRLDirectory, oauth.removeServiceNameFromJWTURI, protoc-gen-go-grpc genServiceComments, benchresult createMap. These have no relationship to attributes.Attributes; the edge appears to be a bare-name collision on some other 'Attributes'. I had to hand-filter the list, and the 'high risk / 127 direct callers' headline is inflated by it."},
    {"tool": "sense_blast", "query": "attributes.Attributes", "note": "retained_via_interfaces carrier attribution is often nonsense: it named grpclb.lbCacheSubConn as the concrete carrier behind weightedroundrobin.endpointWeight's SubConn, and pickfirst_test.stateStoringBalancerBuilder as the carrier for gracefulswitch.lbConfig. The holder+interface columns were reliable; the carrier column was not, and Task 5's whole job was resolving carriers — I had to do that by reading assignment sites myself."},
    {"tool": "sense_graph", "query": "resolver.Endpoint / resolver.State / resolver.Address (direction=callers)", "note": "called_by came back empty for all three with next_steps suggesting 'no callers found — search for dynamic references'. For a plain Go struct that's expected (composed_by was the useful edge), but the empty-set framing plus the suggestion reads like a miss and briefly made me doubt the result."},
    {"tool": "sense_graph", "query": "xds.SetXDSHandshakeClusterName (direction=callers)", "note": "The depth-2 layer returned xds.ignore (internal/xds/xds_test.go:42) with a snippet about strings.HasPrefix that has nothing to do with the traced symbol — a spurious edge I discarded."}
  ],
  "q2_fallbacks": [
    {"tool": "sense_graph", "query": "resolver.Address / resolver.Endpoint / resolver.State composed_by", "fallback": "read", "missing": "composed_by names the holder struct and its line range but not WHICH field holds the carrier or its line. Task 4 explicitly demanded file:line of the retaining field, so I read every struct body — clientconn.go:1242-1276 for curAddr/addrs, balancer/rls/balancer.go:161-208 for resolverState, balancergroup.go:44-74 for ccState, delegatingresolver.go:52-69, priority/balancer_child.go:33-56, lazy.go:71-90, subconn_wrapper.go:33-70, pickfirst.go:150-165 and :873-879. That was roughly ten reads recovering information the composition edge already implies it knows."},
    {"tool": "sense_blast", "query": "attributes.Attributes (retained_via_interfaces)", "fallback": "grep", "missing": "It told me the field and the interface but not the assignment site, and its carrier column was unreliable (see Q1). To resolve each route mechanically for Task 5 I grepped assignment sites myself: 'scWrapper{' / 'subConnWrapper{' / 'balancerWrapper{' / 'subBalancerWrapper{' / 'ClientConn:' / 'subConnToAddr[', landing on clusterimpl.go:605, outlierdetection/balancer.go:483, endpointsharding.go:168, balancergroup.go:314, grpclb_util.go:86. The 'blast a listed holder to go deeper' advice would have cost one call per holder for ~10 holders."},
    {"tool": "sense_graph", "query": "grpc.addrConn (direction=both)", "fallback": "grep", "missing": "Nothing identified acBalancerWrapper as the terminal concrete balancer.SubConn — the linchpin of every Task 5 route. I grepped balancer_wrapper.go for 'func.*NewSubConn|acBalancerWrapper{|ac:|newAddrConnLocked' to establish ccBalancerWrapper.NewSubConn:180 -> newAddrConnLocked:194 -> acBalancerWrapper{ac:ac}:199-201. This is exactly the interface-satisfaction edge the index_caveat admits it misses."},
    {"tool": "sense_blast", "query": "attributes.Attributes", "fallback": "grep", "missing": "No way to ask 'which types implement Equal(o any) bool' — the value-side half of the contract I was reworking. I grepped 'Equal(o any) bool' and got the five production implementers (weight.go:41, hierarchy.go:35, wrrlocality/balancer.go:106, metadata.go:38, channelz/channel.go:120), which became the core of the Task 6 risk ranking."},
    {"tool": "sense_graph", "query": "resolver.Endpoint composed_by", "fallback": "grep", "missing": "No signal on which carriers do or don't have an Equal method. I ran grep 'func (.*Endpoint) Equal|func (.*State) Equal' over resolver/ to establish the negative — that only Address has Equal — which was a load-bearing claim in Task 2."},
    {"tool": "sense_blast", "query": "attributes.Attributes", "fallback": "read", "missing": "completeness said 'partial, hidden: 184' with advice to 'narrow with a direction', but sense_blast exposes no direction parameter. With 184 symbols hidden and no way to page them, I could not treat the blast output as the exhaustive answer Task 4 demanded, so I fell back to per-carrier composed_by plus manual struct reads."}
  ],
  "q3_hints": [
    {"tool": "sense_blast", "query_before": "sense_blast symbol=attributes.Attributes", "query_after": "read struct bodies at clusterimpl.go:560-570, subconn_wrapper.go:33-70, endpointsharding.go:333-348, balancergroup.go:44-74 and grepped for their construction sites", "hint": "retained_note: 'Which satisfier lands at runtime is unverified. Not counted in total_affected; blast a listed holder to go deeper.' The explicit unverified flag is why I did not cite the carrier column in Task 5 and instead traced each route by reading assignments — and that caution paid off, since the carriers it named for endpointWeight and gracefulswitch were wrong."},
    {"tool": "sense_blast", "query_before": "sense_blast symbol=attributes.Attributes (expecting it to be the exhaustive Task 4 answer)", "query_after": "sense_graph symbol=resolver.State direction=callers and sense_graph symbol=resolver.Address direction=callers, run per-carrier instead", "hint": "completeness: 'Partial: total_affected is the true count. Narrow with a direction or query a specific name for the rest.' with hidden:184 — told me the single blast was not exhaustive, so I decomposed the audit carrier by carrier."},
    {"tool": "mcp__sense__sense_status", "query_before": "(session start, no orientation query yet)", "query_after": "sense_search 'immutable metadata attributes attached during name resolution' with language=go", "hint": "key_symbols listed attributes.Attributes with 213 references and callers including cdsbalancer.cdsBalancer — that pre-flagged cdsbalancer as an Attributes holder before I ran any search, and it ended up being the only production struct with a bare *attributes.Attributes field (cdsbalancer.go:143)."}
  ],
  "q4_value": "The retained_via_interfaces block on sense_blast, combined with composed_by depth-2 on the carriers. Task 4 explicitly asked for holders whose field is typed as an interface so that no text search for the metadata type reaches them — that is a query grep structurally cannot express. Sense named clusterimpl.scWrapper, endpointsharding.balancerWrapper, balancergroup.subBalancerWrapper, grpclb.subConnCacheEntry and weightedroundrobin.endpointWeight as SubConn/ClientConn-typed retainers, and I would not have found that set by reading files in the turns available. Second to that: composed_by on attributes.Attributes handed me the three carrier types and ~20 holders in a single call, turning an open-ended repo-wide audit into a verification pass.",
  "q5_improve": "Make composition edges field-level. composed_by tells me 'grpc.addrConn (clientconn.go:1242-1276) composes resolver.Address' but not that the fields are curAddr at :1262 and addrs at :1263 — so for a retention audit I read every struct body anyway, roughly ten reads that ate most of Task 4. Emit the field name and line on each composed_by row, and mark whether it is a direct field, a slice/map element, an embedded interface, or a map key. Second, fix the direct_callers false positives on sense_blast: aes128gcm.Encrypt and protoc-gen-go-grpc genServiceComments as callers of attributes.Attributes look like bare-name collisions, and they inflate the risk headline enough that I stopped trusting the count.",
  "score": 8,
  "score_rationale": "Sense gave me things grep could not have produced in this session — the interface-typed retainer set from retained_via_interfaces and the carrier map from composed_by (Q1, Q4) — but I still needed fallbacks for the two things the audit actually turned on: the retaining field's line number (~10 struct reads) and the terminal acBalancerWrapper -> addrConn edge that no Sense call surfaced (Q2), plus its carrier attribution was wrong often enough that I verified every Task 5 route by hand (Q1 wrong)."
}

